The paper is about developing a learning algorithm for a specific type of model, Relational Logistic Regression (RLR), which is used for modelling multi-relational data. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Weka, an open-source machine learning tool, further supporting the likelihood of it belonging to cs.LG. 

The paper also discusses the incorporation of hidden features about individuals into RLR to boost learning performance, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The use of a modified version of the MovieLens dataset for comparison with other models suggests that the paper could also belong to the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category. 

The paper's focus on modelling multi-relational data and the use of formulae for conditional probability suggests that it could also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper's use of logistic regression and comparison to standard logistic regression models suggests that it could also belong to the Computation and Language (cs.CL) sub-category.
